=========================================
🔥 STACK UNWINDING (C++ EXCEPTION HANDLING)
=========================================

1. What is Stack Unwinding?
----------------------------
- Stack unwinding is the process of cleaning up stack frames
  when an exception is thrown.
- It happens automatically during exception handling in C++.

-----------------------------------------
2. How it works?
-----------------------------------------
When an exception is thrown:

1. Current function stops execution immediately
2. Control moves backward through call stack
3. Each function in reverse order is destroyed
4. Local objects (stack objects) are destructed
5. Matching catch block is searched

-----------------------------------------
3. Example Flow
-----------------------------------------

main()
  └── funcA()
        └── funcB()
              └── funcC()  → throw exception

Flow after throw:

funcC() exits immediately
↓
funcB() is unwound (destructors called)
↓
funcA() is unwound (destructors called)
↓
main() reaches matching catch block

-----------------------------------------
4. Key Point (VERY IMPORTANT)
-----------------------------------------

✔ Stack objects → automatically destroyed
✔ Destructors are called in reverse order
✔ Resources are safely released (RAII works here)

-----------------------------------------
5. Example Code
-----------------------------------------

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Test {
public:
    Test() { cout << "Constructor\n"; }
    ~Test() { cout << "Destructor\n"; }
};

void funcC() {
    Test t;
    throw runtime_error("Error in funcC");
}

void funcB() {
    Test t;
    funcC();
}

void funcA() {
    Test t;
    funcB();
}

int main() {
    try {
        funcA();
    }
    catch (exception &e) {
        cout << "Caught: " << e.what() << endl;
    }
}

-----------------------------------------
Expected Output:
-----------------------------------------
Constructor
Constructor
Constructor
Destructor
Destructor
Destructor
Caught: Error in funcC

-----------------------------------------
6. Why Stack Unwinding is Important?
-----------------------------------------
✔ Prevents resource leaks
✔ Ensures proper destructor calls
✔ Core of RAII (Resource Acquisition Is Initialization)
✔ Makes exception-safe code possible

-----------------------------------------
7. Important Interview Points
-----------------------------------------
✔ Happens only during exception handling
✔ Works only for stack objects
✔ Heap objects are NOT automatically deleted
✔ Destructors MUST NOT throw exceptions
✔ Works automatically (no manual handling needed)

-----------------------------------------
8. Stack Unwinding + RAII Relation
-----------------------------------------
- RAII ensures resources are tied to object lifetime
- During stack unwinding, destructors release resources

Example:
- file close
- mutex unlock
- memory free (via smart pointers)

-----------------------------------------
🔥 ONE-LINE SUMMARY
-----------------------------------------
Stack unwinding = automatic destruction of stack objects
during exception propagation to maintain safety and cleanup.
